For he expresses here the same sentiment as he does to Titus, when hc says, “that the kindness and love of God towards man appeared, not by works of righteousness which we have done, but according to his mercy.'’ (o) The very persons, who argue that Paul, in denying that it isos him that willeth or os him that runneth‚ irn- plies that tlrereis some williug aud some running, would not allow me to use the same mode of reasoning, that we have done some good works, because Paul denies that we have ob· tained the favour of God by any works which we have done. But if they perceive a flaw in this argumentation, let them open their eyes, and they will perceive a similar fallacy in their own. For the argument on which Angustiae rests the dispute is unauswerable: “ If it be said, that it is not of him that willeth, nor of him that runneth, merely because neither our williug nor our running is sufficient, it may, on the eon· trary, be retorted, that it is not of the mercy of God, because that does not act alone.'’ ( p) 'Phelatter position being absurd, Angustiae justly concludes the meaning of this passage to be, that there is no good will in man, unless it be prepared by the Lord; not but that we ought to will and to run, but because God works in us both the one and the other.
